org.jsapar.text

Class BooleanFormat

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.text.Format
      • org.jsapar.text.BooleanFormat
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Cloneable

    public class BooleanFormat
extends Format
    Format class that can be used to parse or format boolean values based on a true and a false value. For instance, you may have a text where Y is supposed to mean true and N is supposed to mean false. In that case you can create an instance of this class in this way: 
     
 BooleanFormat format = new BooleanFormat("Y", "N");
 assert format.format(true).equals("Y");
 assert format.format(false).equals("N");
 assert format.parse("Y");
 assert !format.parse("N");
    You can provide an array of valid true and false strings. In that case the first true and the first false strings are used when formatting.
    See Also:
    Serialized Form

      • BooleanFormat

        public BooleanFormat()
        Creates a default instance where the text "true" is the true value and "false" is the false value.
        • Optional true values while parsing are: "on", "1", "yes", "y"
        • Optional false values while parsing are: "off", "0", "no", "n"

      • BooleanFormat

        public BooleanFormat(String[] trueValues,
                     String[] falseValues)
        Creates a formatter for boolean values where multiple values are accepted as true or false values. When parsing, the supplied values are tested for equality against the input in following order:
        1. The first true value.
        2. The first false value.
        3. The rest of the true values are tested in supplied order.
        4. The rest of the false values are tested in supplied order.
        Parameters:
        trueValues - An array of all of the strings that represents the true value. The first item in the array is used when formatting.
        falseValues - An array of all of the strings that represents the false value. The first item in the array is used when formatting.
